@NODE Introduction "Introduction"

Multi-Talk  (or MTalk for short) is a multi-user teleconference system
for  the  Amiga(tm)  series  of computers.  It can run on any bulletin
board  system  (BBS)  that supports standard input and output, or even
without a BBS.  (See @{" Running Without A BBS " Link Running_Without_A_BBS})

The  reason why MTalk was created was because there was, until now, no
decent  conferencing  software  for  the  Amiga(tm) which provides the
features  and  flexibilities  of  MTalk.  Not to mention, there was no
conference  software that can almost run on any BBS.  MTalk's power is
unmatched in any other teleconference system.  Here is why:

(in no particular order)

o Unlimited users, channels, and independent conferences.
o Command line editing with command history.
o Transparent inter-BBS networking.  (See @{" Networking " Link Networking})
o BBS independence.  (See @{" Running Without A BBS " Link Running_Without_A_BBS})
o Over 60 built-in @{" commands " Link commands}, and external command @{" doors " Link doors}.
o AREXX port for external control. (See @{" AREXX Port " Link AREXX_Port})
o Text windows for simultaneous input/output.
o User to user private chats with text windows.
o Can be configured as a SysOp chat program.
o Command aliases for personalized commands.
o Variables for setting user environment.
o Task switching between host BBS and MTalk.
o ANSI color support.
o Command @{" scripts " Link scripts}, such as login and logout scripts.
o Action commands. (See @{" Actions " Link Actions})
o @{" Profanity filter " Link Profanity_filter}.
o Channels may be private (by invitations only), user limited, and
  moderated.
o User may ignore other users.
o Private messages ("whispers")
o Message logging.
o Command output redirection.
o Pattern matching.

All  documentation  in  this file are directed to the system operator,
not other users of MTalk.  Users of MTalk should read the on-line help
instead.

Note,  since  MTalk is so complex, it's likely I will miss documenting
certain  things.   If  you  feel  I  have  not covered certain aspects
enough,  please  send  me  mail,  so I can revise this document.  (See
@{" Contact Address " Link Contact_Address})


@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements "Requirements"

This  program  runs  on  any Amiga(tm) with version 2.04 of the OS.  A
system with 512K would suffice.  In addition to the executable size of
@{" MTalk  client " Link MTalk__client}  and  @{" MTalkD server " Link MTalkD_server}, they take 10K and around 40K of
data  for  each program invocation, respectively.  The stack space for
MTalkD  should  be  10K or higher, and 4K for the client.  To minimize
memory  usage,  it  is  best to have the programs 'MTalk' and 'MTalkD'
made memory resident.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation "Installation"

You  must  put  MTalk  and  its  accompanying  files into the assigned
directory  called  DOORS:ASI.   DOORS:   is the proposed directory for
doors  (or  BBS  utilities)  used  by  many  system operators and door
programmers.   ASI  is  a  directory  where  you  should  put  the BBS
utilities  written  by  me.   You must also create several directories
within DOORS:ASI.  The directories are:

bin/    -- executable files
config/ -- configuration files
data/   -- data files
doc/    -- documentation
help/   -- help files
key/    -- key files
libs/   -- runtime libraries
log/    -- log files
script/ -- scripts files
text/   -- miscellaneous text files
user/   -- data on each user

Most  of these directories will be created for you, when you unarchive
MTalk.

The files pertaining to MTalk are as follows:

bin/MTalk
  -- This is the client program each user calls.
bin/MTalkD
  -- This is the server (or "daemon") program.
bin/PortConfig
  -- Serial port/modem configuration program for you to set up
     inter-bbs linking.  (See @{" Networking " Link Networking})
bin/MTNetSer
  -- Network link server for serial.device.
bin/mycat
  -- A command used by script/MTalk.rexx, which copies data from
     standard input to standard output.
config/MTNetSer.hosts
  -- List of network systems and their phone numbers, for networking.
     (See @{" Networking " Link Networking})
config/MTNetSer.in.passwd
  -- Passwords for system calling in, during networking.
     (See @{" Networking " Link Networking})
config/MTNetSer.out.passwd
  -- Our passwords to use on remote systems, during networking.
     (See @{" Networking " Link Networking})
config/MTNetSer.port
  -- Default  serial  port  configuration  file  for linking  multiple
     systems running with MTalk.
data/actions.mts
  -- An MTalk Script to install all @{" actions " Link actions}.
doc/PortConfig.doc
  -- Documentation for the serial port configuration program.
doc/MTalk.doc
  -- Documentation for MTalk in text format.
doc/MTalk.guide
  -- Documentation for MTalk in AmigaGuide format.
doc/MTalk.guide.info
  -- Icon for above.
help/MTalk/
  -- Help files for all the built-in commands, plus door commands.
key/MTalk.key
  -- The key for a registered version of MTalk.
libs/rawin.library
  -- input library used by the MTalk client.
     You should copy LIBS/rawin.library into LIBS: or put
     "assign libs: DOORS:ASI/libs add" into your "startup-sequence"
     file.
script/MTalk.rexx
  -- An AREXX script which simulates the MTalk client program.
     (See @{" AREXX Port " Link AREXX_Port})
script/MTChat.batch
  -- AmigaDOS batch file to launch MTalk as a SysOp-User chat program.
script/server-startup.mts
  -- The script gets run everytime the MTalkD server starts.
     It is also executed when "/REHASH" is executed from within MTalk.
script/user-exit.mts
  -- MTalk executes this script everytime a user exits.
     It is executed in the user's environment so the commands in the
     script must be accessible to the user.
script/user-startup.mts
  -- MTalk  executes this script (in the user's environment) everytime
     a user enters MTalk.
text/MTalk.motd
  -- Message  Of  The  Day  text  file you may want your users to read
     everytime  they  use  MTalk.   It  is  sort  of  like a news file
     informing  the  user  of  any changes to the system, like the new
     things (@{" doors " Link doors}) you may want to add to MTalk.
user/<user_name>/env.mts
  -- User's script to set up environment.
user/<user_name>/login.mts
  -- User's login script.
user/<user_name>/logout.mts
  -- User's logout script called from script/user-exit.mts.

All filenames ending with .mts are MTalk Scripts. (See @{" Scripts " Link Scripts})


@ENDNODE

@NODE Command_Line_Usage "Command Line Usage"

@{" MTalk Client " Link MTalk_Client}
@{" MTalkD Server " Link MTalkD_Server}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MTalk_Client "MTalk Client"

Usage: MTalk <key> <value> ...

important keys:

 NICK   User's alias/handle/nickname/etc.  This name may be changed by
  -n    the  /NICK  command  if you chose to make it accessible to the
        users.   Nick  should  be 35 characters or less.  For example,
        hacker.
 REAL   User's   real   name.   The  name  can  be  "First  Last",  or
  -r    First_Last.  The name must be 35 characters in length or less.
        If  the alias of the user is not supplied, the NAME is used as
        the alias as well.  For example, John Smith.
 UID    User's  ID.   This  is only needed when multiple MTalk systems
  -u    are  linked.   UID  should  be  35  characters  or  less.  For
        example, jsmith.
 LEVEL  User's  access level.  This should be passed from the host BBS
  -l    software.   Access to conference commands is strictly based on
        access  levels.   Default  is 0.  The minimum and maximum user
        levels are 0 and 32767, respectively.
 SERVER Server  name,  only applicable to the unlimited users version.
  -s    Default  is  MTalkD.   This  is used for separate, independent
        conferences.   For  example,  you  might  have  MALL  handle a
        conference for teenagers and BAR handle a conference for older
        people.   This  is  particular useful when these two groups of
        people  don't  mix.   When  a user in the teenagers conference
        checks  out  who  is on-line in the conference, he or she will
        not  see  who  is  on-line  in  the older people's conference.
        Whispering  across  conferences  is  not  possible.   Think of
        channels as rooms, conferences as houses, and servers as house
        keepers.  The more servers, the more houses!
 ALTOUT Alternative  output  filename.  This  option is for the SysOp,
  -a    allowing  him/her  to  type and see message output at the same
        time without using "text windows".
 PRI    Priority of program.  (default 0)
  -p

Note  that "MTalk" without any arguments will have a random name given
to  the  user, in the form of "UserX", where X is from 0 to 99.  Other
keys  and  values  are  used  to  pass  to doors you have have set up.
Keywords are not case sensitive.  Note that the name and alias will be
copied  from  the  arguments and changed, from the form "user_name" or
"USER_NAME" to "User Name".  That is, the first letter of each word is
capitalized and the rest of the word will be in lower case.  Also, any
"_"  characters  will  be  replaced with spaces.  The key words can be
replaced with their shorter forms, such as "-n" for "NICK".

Example:

MTalk REAL "Joe Sixpack" NICK "Drunk" LEVEL 1 PORT TTY0
MTalk -r "Joe Sixpack" -n "Drunk" -l 1 PORT TTY0


@ENDNODE

@NODE MTalkD_Server "MTalkD Server"

Usage: MTalkD <key> <value> ...

keys:

 KEYNAME    Which of the user's name (NICK/REAL/UID) is the key?
  -k        (default REAL)
 HOST       Name of this system.  (default 'home')
  -h        Used for networking.
 SERVER     Server name.  (default MTalkD)
  -s
 HOMEDIR    Where all data files are kept.  (default DOORS:ASI)
  -d        If  you  run  two  different  BBS's  you may want to set a
            different path for each server.
 PRI        Priority of program.  (default 0)
  -p

Multiple MTalk servers may be started by specifying a different SERVER
name  for each server.  All clients must use these names for reference
when  connecting with the servers.  It is therefore possible to create
multiple,  separate,  and  independent conferences.  MTalkD without an
argument  starts a server with an identification name "MTalkD".  Since
the  server  does not detach from the CLI, it is recommended it is run
by  "runback  >NIL:   <NIL:   MTalkD".   The  SERVER  argument is only
effective with the unlimited users version.  Once a server is started,
you  may  type "break <server_process_num>" (type "status" to find the
CLI  process  number  for the server) or type "/DIE" inside MTalk.  If
there  are  users  online, it'll try to kick them out.  The server can
only  quit  if there are no users in the conference.  If you are using
MTalk  on  a  "big"  system,  you  should  set  the server to a higher
priority  than  any  of  the  clients.   A task priority of 0 for each
client and 1 for the server would be good.

Example:

run >NIL: <NIL: MTalkD KEYNAME REAL HOST mybbs HOMEDIR WORK:DATA


@ENDNODE

@NODE Running_Without_A_BBS "Running Without A BBS"

A  way  to  run  MTalk  without  a  BBS  is to use an auxiliary device
handler.   This  type  of handler allows a program to send and receive
data  to  and  from  the serial port.  The AUX:  device by Steve Drew,
from  Fish  Disk  #79  does  a  nice  job.  Note the AUX:  supplied by
Commodore does not work properly.

Type the following commands in AmigaShell:
mount AUX:
MTalk <AUX: >>AUX:  (See @{" MTalk Client " Link MTalk_Client})

Execute  the  last  command  only when the dial-in user has connected.
When  MTalk  is  running, all of its inputs and outputs will be going
through the serial port.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Commands "Commands"

The  commands  the user executes are documented as on-line help.  They
are stored in DOORS:ASI/help/MTalk/.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Scripts "Scripts"

Like  a  Shell, MTalk supports command scripts.  MTalk scripts usually
end with the ".mts" file extension.  There are three standard types of
scripts.   The  first  one  is  the  server  script,  which the server
executes  when  it is first launched.  The second one is global, which
every  user  executes when he/she enter the conference.  The script is
DOORS:ASI/script/user-startup.mts.   The  default  command aliases are
defined  here.   The other script is the one that can be customized by
each  user.  Note that at the present, there is no way for the user to
edit this file from within the conference.  You may want to provide an
editor  door  to  accomplish  this task.  The user script is stored as
DOORS:ASI/user/<user_name>/login.mts.   The  global script is similiar
to  "s:startup-sequence",  while  the  local  script  is  similiar  to
"s:shell-startup".  Scripts may be called from other scripts.

To   configure  user  accessible  scripts,  use  /CONFIG  SCRIPT  <ID>
<filename>,  where  <ID>  is some symbolic name (e.g., USER-LOGIN) you
give  to a <filename>.  When a user executes a script (with /EXEC), it
is done so in his environment, with his access level, etc.  Therefore,
it  is  not necessary to give access levels for scripts.  To execute a
script by filename, rather than by ID, you must be in /POWER mode.  If
the argument you give to /EXEC is an ID, it will be looked up, else it
is treated as an absolute filename.

There  is  a  special  feature  scripts  have  that  you can not do by
executing  commands  on  the  command line.  You can pass arguments to
scripts  as  if  you are executing a program.  In your scripts you can
retrieve  the  command  arguments  by using the "$<num>[+]" codes.  To
access  argument  1  you would use "$1".  $0 is the script name.  Read
the  section  on DOORS (below) for more information on how to retrieve
arguments.  All the user needs to do is type "/EXEC <script> arg1 arg2
...".  For example, "/EXEC MYSCRIPT This is a test."


@ENDNODE

@NODE Doors "Doors"

MTalk  was  developed  with  configurability  in  mind.  With the door
feature,  you  can  set  up  a  multitude  of external CLI commands or
information  files that the user can access.  Access to these commands
will be based on user levels.  They are executed the same way built-in
commands  are.   Starting  with  version  1.00  of MTalk all doors are
configurable with script files.  The /CONFIG command will help you set
up  doors.   The  usage  format  for  /CONFIG is:  /CONFIG DOOR <name>
<level> [<]<DOS-command> | *<script-file>

/CONFIG is used to configure MTalk, and the sub-command "DOOR" sets up
doors.   <name>  is the name of the door.  If <name> already exists in
the  configured  doors, the old door will be replaced.  <level> is the
access  level  required  to  execute  the  door.  <DOS-command> is the
AmigaDOS  command  to  execute.  The optional '<' character forces the
MTalkD  server  to execute the command, and not the MTalk client.  All
output will then be sent to the client.  It is recommended '<' is used
for  batch  programs  (e.g., who-is-online) that can finish running in
less  than  a  second.  Note that the server will not respond to other
user's  requests  until  it  has  finished executing the command.  The
<DOS-command>  to  execute  may  contain  special codes that are to be
interpreted  before  the  resulting  DOS  command  is executed.  These
specials  codes allow arguments that are invoked with the MTalk client
to  be passed to the door.  For example, if you pass PORT as the "key"
and  as  the "value" (PORT may be the terminal line the user is logged
into), you may use this information as arguments to the door.  Special
codes  begin  with  the  '$'  (dollar)  sign,  and  may  be numbers or
keywords.   Numbers  are  used  to pass arguments supplied by the user
within  MTalk,  and  names are passed by the command invocation of the
MTalk  client.  Number codes start with 0, indicating the door command
the  user  executed,  continue  with  1,  the  first argument the user
supplied,  and  so on.  A '+' (plus) sign indicate all those arguments
past a certain argument.

When  you  want  a  door  to  execute  MTalk @{" scripts " Link scripts} (typically with
extension  .mts),  you simply put a "*" before the <script-file>.  For
example,   *DOORS:ASI/SCRIPT/TEST.mts.   Please  refer  to  the  above
section  for  more  information on MTalk scripts.  Again, you can pass
arguments to the script in the same manner as /EXEC.

Examples:
/CONFIG DOOR page 0 <DOORS:ASI/bin/TelePage \$REAL \$1 \$2+
/CONFIG DOOR test 0 *DOORS:ASI/SCRIPT/TEST.mts

Make  sure  you  put a \ before the '$' to ensure that the variable is
not  to  be  interpreted as a variable when /CONFIG is executed.  What
you  want  is  to  have  those  variables  interpreted before the DOOR
commands are executed.

Assuming the @{" MTalk client " Link MTalk_client} was executed as: MTalk REAL John_Smith

When the user executes:
user> /page joe This is a test.

This is what is actually executed:
DOORS:ASI/bin/TelePage John_Smith joe This is a test.

To  summarize,  the  "$" symbol introduces a variable or an conference
command line argument.  They are defined as follows:

$<variable> - will simply be replaced with <variable>'s actual value.
              This is passed as an argument when executing MTalk.
              For example, $NAME is a variable, $LEVEL is a variable,
              but $10 is not.
$<num> - will be replaced with argument number <num> of the user's
         command line.
$<num>+ - will be replace with arguments from the user's command
          line starting at <num>.

Note that internal environment variables will not replace $<variable>.
That  is, only those that are included when executing MTalk are passed
to the doors.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Actions "Actions"

Actions  are  special "commands" that each user can perform on himself
or  herself,  or  other  users.  The actions file is actually a script
file  (see  @{" Scripts " Link Scripts}),  called  DOORS:ASI/data/actions.mts,  which is
executed  from  DOORS:ASI/script/server-script.  Each action entry has
the    form:     <name>   <level>   <first-person>   [<second-person>]
<third-person>.  Any argument after <level> should include quotes.

The arguments are defined as:

<name> is the name of the action, eg. "kick"
<level> is the minimum user level required to do this action.
<first-person> is the text the action performer will see.
<second-person> is the text the person you are doing the action to
                will see.  If this argument is missing, it is assumed
                the action requires no performee.
<third-person> is what the rest of the users will see when you perform
               the action to.

<first-person>,<second-person>,<third-person>  can  have the following
tokens:

%r - Will replace the token with the name of receiver of the action.
%s - Will replace the token with the name of the action performer.
%t - Will replace with "his" or "her", according to the sex of the
     receiver.
%u - Will replace with "his" or "her", according to the sex of the
     performer.
%v - Will replace with "him" or "her", according to the sex of the
     receiver.
%w - Will replace with "him" or "her", according to the sex of the
     performer.
%x - Will replace with "he" or "she", according to the sex of the
     receiver.
%y - Will replace with "he" or "she", according to the sex of the
     performer.
%z - Will replace with the text supplied by the user.

@{" Construction Example #1 " Link Construction_Example_#1}
@{" Application  Example #1 " Link Application__Example_#1}
@{" Construction Example #2 " Link Construction_Example_#2}
@{" Application  Example #2 " Link Application__Example_#2}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Construction_Example_#1 "Construction Example #1"
/config door ask 0 "What's your sign?" "%s is asking for your sign!"
                   "%s is asking %r for %t sign!"

@ENDNODE

@NODE Application__Example_#1 "Application  Example #1"
Three users are on-line, namely "John", "Mary", and "Peter".

Situation #1: John asks Mary for her sign.

John> .ask Mary
-+- What's your sign? -+-
Mary>
-+- John is asking for your sign! -+-
Peter>
-+- John is asking Mary for her sign! -+-

Situation #2: Mary asks John for his sign.

Mary> .ask John
-+- What's your sign? -+-
John>
-+- Mary is asking for your sign! -+-
Peter>
-+- Mary is asking John for his sign! -+-

@ENDNODE

@NODE Construction_Example_#2 "Construction Example #2"
/config door me 0 "%s %z" "%s %z"

@ENDNODE

@NODE Application__Example_#2 "Application  Example #2"
John> .me is tired and needs some sleep.
-+- John is tired and needs some sleep. -+-
Mary>
-+- John is tired and needs some sleep. -+-
Peter>
-+- John is tired and needs some sleep. -+-


@ENDNODE

@NODE Profanity_Filter "Profanity Filter"

A  lot  of  people  like swearing, but most of them don't think before
they do it.  As a result, their listeners often get insulted.  This is
where  the  profanity  filter  comes  in.  The way the filter works is
this:   A  swear  message gets through only if both the sender and the
receiver  has their filter turned off.  If either one has it turned on
it  won't get through.  Think of it as a pipe, where water cannot flow
through  if  either  end  of  the pipe is blocked.  The filter file is
DOORS:ASI/data/MTalk.filter.  The text file containings words (with or
without  wildcards)  that are to be matched with each of the words the
user types.

In  order  to create an effective filtering system you must know about
AmigaDOS   pattern   matching.    Consult  your  AmigaDOS  manual  for
explanations.   If  you  are  unfamiliar  with  them, either leave the
default filter file alone, or get a friend, who is familiar with them,
to  edit  the  filter  file.   If  you  feel that there are other very
popular offensive words that I have missed, but should include, please
let me know.

@{" Filter Example File " Link Filter_Example_File}
@{" Filter Test " Link Filter_Test}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Filter_Example_File "Filter Example File"

An example of a filter file is:

bitch
ass
ass#(!|.|,|'?)
ass#(-)hole#(!|.|,|?)

@ENDNODE

@NODE Filter_Test "Filter Test"

Let's suppose that a user called "Badmouth" types:

Badmouth> you bitch
Swear word(s) detected!
Badmouth> ass
Swear word(s) detected!
Badmouth> associate
--sent---
Badmouth> compass
--sent---
Badmouth> asshole
Swear word(s) detected!
Badmouth> ass-hole
Swear word(s) detected!


@ENDNODE

@NODE Message_Port_Names "Message Port Names"

Each  MTalk  server  opens  three  message  ports.   This first is the
standard  server port the client program 'MTalk' connects with.  It is
named  by  default  'MTalkD'  when  MTalkD  is run.  It can however be
changed  to  anything you want by the SERVER switch when executing the
server  program.   All  other port names are based on the stanard port
name.   The  @{" AREXX port " Link AREXX_port}  has  the  '_REXX'  suffix, so a server with
standard  port  name  'MTalkD'  will have an AREXX port 'MTalkD_REXX'.
The  third  port  is  the  @{" MTalk networking " Link MTalk_networking} port, which has a '_NET'
suffix.   A  server  with  'MTalkD'  standard  port  name  will have a
'MTalkD_NET'  networking  port  name.   This  port will be used by the
network  server to communicate with the MTalk server.  It is important
that  you  use the correct ports by the correct programs, or else your
system can crash!


@ENDNODE

@NODE AREXX_Port "AREXX Port"

Anything you can do from inside MTalk you can also do from outside, by
using  MTalk's  AREXX port.  Each MTalk server has its own AREXX port.
Accessing  the  AREXX port is very simple and straight forward.  There
are  only  four  commands  you  need  to learn to completely control a
server.   These four commands and their usage (using AmigaDOS template
convention) are:

EXE ID/K CMD/F
 This  command  allows the AREXX client to execute a an MTalk command.

 ID  is  the  AREXX client ID.  It is not required if you just want to
 execute a command and then exit immediately.  If ID is not specified,
 user  startup/cleanup  scripts  are  not executed, so execution is as
 quickly as possible.  This ID can be anything you want, but make sure
 it  is unique so that there is no one using it while an AREXX command
 is executed.

 CMD  is  the  MTalk  command  to  send to the server.  It is the same
 command as if typed from the MTalk command line.

LOGIN ID/K MSGFILE/K
 Sometimes   you   need   to  execute  a  series  of  commands  before
 disconnecting  from  the  AREXX  port.   You must use this command to
 formally register the AREXX client into MTalk's user list.  ID is the
 client's  ID.   MSGFILE is the file where you want the server to send
 all  text  output  to.  The server first attempts to open MSGFILE for
 append,  but  if it fails it'll open for write (newfile).

LOGOUT ID/K
 Logout the AREXX client ID logged in by LOGIN.

SENDMSG ID/K START/K STOP/K
 Tell  the  AREXX  server  to  send  client text by writing to MSGFILE
 specified  in  LOGIN.   START  (by  default) starts sending, and STOP
 stops  sending.  You generally don't need to use this command, unless
 you intend to change MSGFILE and don't want the server to interfer.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Networking "Networking"

MTalk's  networking  support allows two or more MTalk equipped systems
to  be  linked  together  to provide more exciting conferences.  Since
MTalk  is  built  around  a client-server model, it is natural to have
networking  support  following the same path.  A networking server for
the serial device is included, and in the future other servers such as
TCP/IP  may  be  added.   Since networking is new and experimental for
version  1.0  and  it is difficult for me to test it (can't hog up two
phone  lines  until late night).  It may or may not work as you expect
it.  Your feedback is more than welcome.

There are only a few things you need to do in order to get your system
up  and running with another system.  The first step is to set up your
modem  file  with  the  "PortConfig" program.  MTNetSer (MTalk Network
Server)  will use this modem file.  You should read DOC/PortConfig.doc
before  you  run  the program.  The modem file you created can also be
used  for  TeleVal  callback  verifier  and  GateTerm  outdialer  (not
included  in  archive).   (See @{" Programs Released " Link Programs_Released}) If you are already
running  with  one  of  these programs you can just use the same modem
file  for  MTNetSer.   The default modem file is CONFIG/MTNetSer.port.
It  is created for the internal serial.device running with a 2400 baud
modem.

After the modem file is configured, you must set up the password files
for  systems  you  want  to  network.  There are two files you need to
change,   CONFIG/MTNetSer.in.passwd   and  CONFIG/MTNetSer.out.passwd.
MTNetSer.in.passwd stores the passwords for remote systems calling in.
For example, when a remote system calls in, its password will be asked
(remote   system   looks   up   its   password   for  your  system  in
MTNetSer.out.passwd),  and  it  will  be compared with the password in
MTNetSer.in.passwd.   If the password is incorrect, the calling system
will  be  disconnected.  MTNetSer.out.passwd stores the passwords your
system  uses  when  it  calls out.  For example, when you call out the
remote  system  will  ask  for  your  password,  you  look  it  up  in
MTNetSer.out.passwd,   and   the   remote   system   compares   it  in
MTNetSer.in.passwd.  The format for both password files is <system-id>
<passwd>  for  each  system  per line, where <system-id> is a short ID
(e.g., tfbbs) and <password> is the unencrypted password.

Now,  you  will  need  to  add some systems to your host database file
CONFIG/MTNetSer.hosts.    Each   line   of   the  file  specifies  the
<system-id>  <system-name>  <phone-no> of a system.  When you call out
to a system, you may specify its phone number or its ID.

Next,  you will need to launch the network server (MTNetSer).  Here is
how to use MTNetSer:

Usage: BIN/MTNetSer <key> <value> ...

keys:

 MYPORT      server port name (default is MTNetSer)
  -m
 CLIENTPORT  client's port name (default is MTalkD_NET)
  -c
 PORTFILE    port data filename
  -p         (default is DOORS:ASI/CONFIG/MTNetSer.port)
 CHECKCD     whether to check carrier detect (default is YES)
  -d

If  you are only connecting with one system, you can pretty much leave
the defaults alone.  MYPORT allows you to name the network server.  If
you are running more than one network server, you must give each one a
different  port  name.   CLIENTPORT  specifies  which MTalk server the
network  server  belongs  to.   PORTFILE specifies which modem file to
use.   CHECKCD  determines if a connection to another system should be
permitted if the Carrier Detect pin of the serial port is off.  If you
are connecting two computers with a null modem cable missing a CD pin,
you  should  specify  CHECKCD  NO.  For example, to launch the server,
execute   "run   DOORS:ASI/BIN/MTNetSer   MYPORT  MTNetSer  CLIENTPORT
MTalkD_NET".  When the network server is launched, it is ready to call
out or allow another system to call in.

From MTalk use /OPEN to call out to other systems.  For example, /OPEN
MTNetSer  434-3665  would  tell  network  server  whose  port  name is
"MTNetSer"  to call the system numbered 434-3665.  Of course you don't
have to remember the phone number if you give it an ID and store it in
MTNetSer.hosts.   For  example, if tfbbs's number is 434-3665, you can
/OPEN MTNetSer tfbbs.

If  you  are  networking  you must give your system an ID, and it must
also be known to those systems you want to connect with.  This ID must
be   passed   to   the   MTalkD   server  by  executing  "MTalkD  HOST
<your-system-id> ..."


@ENDNODE

@NODE Bugs_&_Updates "Bugs & Updates"

Known Bugs:

The  networking  protocol  I developed is primitive and slow (even for
modems  running at 14.4 kps).  The speed is acceptable for normal chat
messages.   There  is  a  bug  with  using  the /TALK command over the
network.  Make sure "/config TalkOverNet Y" is NEVER executed from the
MTalk command line or through a script.  If "/config TalkOverNet Y" is
executed, and a user /TALKs over the network, your machine will crash.
I  hope  to  get  the  problem  solved  on future releases, as well as
including AmiTCP/IP support too.

Updates:

Registered  users  are  privileged to free updates (excluding magnetic
media  cost  and  postal  charges), when they are ready, for ONE year,
from  the  day of purchase.  Bugs will be fixed, but I make no promise
that  new  features  will  be  added.   After  one  year, updates will
possibly  require  a  nominal  fee.   Note  that as a student, I don't
always  have free time, especially when school is in session to update
the software.


@ENDNODE

